,&F%F&^$F+$!+>3#G?\"F0F&F&F%F&,&F%F&$\"+k*4KN\"F0!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 380 "A related theorem about finding roots of polynomials (equivale
ntly factoring polynomials into a product of linear factors) asserts t
hat if the polynomial has real coefficients -- all of the polynomials \+
we have considered (and will consider) have had real coefficients -- t
hen any complex roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For
 example, both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT 
-1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in c
onjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new polyno
mials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show \+
that the any complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs
." }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 115 "For demonstration purposes it is very h
andy to be able to construct polynomials with predetermined roots.  Us
e the " }{TEXT 258 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 58 " command to construct a po
lynomial with roots   -2, 5, 5, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "-1/2" "6#,$*&\"\"\"F
%\"\"#!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 71 ", 1+I and  1-I.  (Here the \"5, 5\" indic
ates that 5 is a \"double root\".)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 307 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 308 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 46 "4.  Binomial Theorem.  Use the \+
Maple command  " }{TEXT 290 6 "expand" }{TEXT 256 2 "  " }{TEXT -1 34 
"to calculate the expansion of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%
\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 63 "    for values n=1..10 .  In eac
h case use the Maple command   " }{TEXT 257 7 "coeffs " }{TEXT 292 1 "
 " }{TEXT -1 84 "to pick off the coefficients.   For example,  if n=5 \+
we would execute the following:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 27 "expand((a+b)^5);\ncoeffs(%);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "
6#,.*$)%\"aG\"\"&\"\"\"F(*(F'F()F&\"\"%F(%\"bGF(F(*(\"#5F()F&\"\"$F()F
,\"\"#F(F(*(F.F()F&F2F()F,F0F(F(*(F'F(F&F()F,F+F(F(*$)F,F'F(F(" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6(\"#5\"\"&F#\"\"\"F%F$" }}}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "Do the rest from 1 to 10.   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to use a " }{TEXT 291 9 "for loop \+
" }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task since we are doing a repetitive
 calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 29 "Note:  Also, the the c
ommand " }{TEXT 293 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 15 " unfortunately " }{TEXT 
294 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off the coefficients in order." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }
{TEXT 260 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a formula for fin
ding the coefficients of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" 
"6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " }{TEXT 295 1 
"n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious that the coefficient of \+
 " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^k*b^(n-k);" "6#*&)%\"aG%\"kG\"\"\")%\"bG,&%\"nGF'
F&!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 296 1 "k" }{TEXT 
-1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 297 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is given by the nu
